    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"8-79\">\n<h2>8-79</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 5, Section 4: Graphing Quadratic Functions</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Connects graphing form of a quadratic to vertex location and standard form.</div>\n<div><p>The following functions are also quadratic functions.</p>\n<div><div><ol class=\"lower-roman\" type=\"i\"><li><p>$y=3(x-2)^2-5$</p></li></ol></div><div><ol class=\"lower-roman\" start=\"2\" type=\"i\"><li><p>$f(x)=-2(x+4)^2+3$</p></li></ol></div></div>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Verify that both equations are quadratic by rewriting them in standard quadratic form. Remember the Order of Operations! How could you verify on your calculator that you rewrote the functions correctly?</p></li><li><p>Use the graph and table on your graphing calculator to find the vertex of each function. Compare the vertex to its equation. What do you notice?</p></li><li><p>Without graphing, can you predict the vertex of $y=\\frac{1}{2}(x+3)^2+2$? Check your conjecture by making a graph with your calculator.</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
